%I A397691 #13 Jul 06 2026 09:08:28
%S A397691 1,3,5,9,15,31,51,103,191,375,719,1439,2799,5599,11071,22111,43967,
%T A397691 87935,175295,350591,700159,1400191,2798335,5596671,11188991,22377983,
%U A397691 44747775,89495039,178973695,357947391,715860991,1431721983,2863378431,5726754815
%N A397691 Number of orbits of nonzero binary algebraic forms of degree n with coefficients in the field with two elements, under the action of SL(2, 2).
%C A397691 Adding 1 to each term (which corresponds to including the zero form) provably gives A060553 (shifted by one). This coincidence reflects the isomorphism between D3 and SL(2, 2).
%H A397691 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A397691/b397691.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000</a>
%H A397691 <a href="/index/Rec#order_07">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (3,0,-4,-2,0,12,-8).
%F A397691 a(n) = (2^(n+1) + 3*2^(1 + floor(n/2)) + 2*2^(1 + floor(n/3) - (n%3)%2))/6 - 1.
%F A397691 a(n) = A060553(n+1) - 1.
%e A397691 Any two linear forms are equivalent up to changes of variables, hence a(1) = 1. There are three orbits of quadratic forms, containing x^2, xy and x^2 + xy + y^2, hence a(2) = 3.
%t A397691 LinearRecurrence[{3, 0, -4, -2, 0, 12, -8}, {1, 3, 5, 9, 15, 31, 51}, 35] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Jul 06 2026 *)
%o A397691 (Python) def a(n): return (2**(n+1) + 3*2**(1 + (n//2)) + 2*2**(1 + (n//3) - (n%3)%2))//6 - 1
%Y A397691 Cf. A060553
%K A397691 nonn,easy,changed
%O A397691 1,2
%A A397691 _Jonas Karlsson_, Jul 05 2026
%E A397691 Extended by _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jul 05 2026 using data from A060553.
